{{main|Taxonomy of lemurs}}
{{mainlist|List of lemur species}}
From a taxonomic standpoint, the term "lemur" originally referred to the genus ''Lemur'', which currently contains only the [[ring-tailed lemur]]. The term is now used in the [[colloquialism|colloquial]] sense in reference to all Malagasy primates.{{Sfn|Rowe|1996|p=27}}

Lemur taxonomy is controversial, and not all experts agree, particularly with the recent increase in the number of recognized species.{{R|2007Yoder|2009Groeneveld|2007Tattersall}}  According to [[Russell Mittermeier]], the president of [[Conservation International]] (CI), taxonomist [[Colin Groves]], and others, there are nearly 100&nbsp;recognized species or subspecies of extant (or living) lemur, divided into five families and 15&nbsp;genera.{{R|2008MittermeierGroves}} Because genetic data indicates that the recently extinct subfossil lemurs were closely related to living lemurs,{{R|2005Karanth}} an additional three families, eight genera, and 17&nbsp;species can be included in the total.{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=37<U+2013>51}}{{R|2009Gommery}}  In contrast, other experts have labeled this as [[taxonomic inflation]],{{r|2007Tattersall}} instead preferring a total closer to 50 species.{{r|2007Yoder}}

The classification of lemurs within the suborder Strepsirrhini is equally controversial, although the most experts agree on the same [[phylogenetic tree]].  In one taxonomy, infraorder Lemuriformes contains all living strepsirrhines in two superfamilies, Lemuroidea for all lemurs and Lorisoidea for the lorisoids ([[Lorisidae|lorisids]] and galagos).{{R|2006Godinot}}{{Sfn|Cartmill|2010|p=15}}  Alternatively, the lorisoids are sometimes placed in their own infraorder, Lorisiformes, separate from the lemurs.{{Sfn|Hartwig|2011|pp=20<U+2013>21}}  In another taxonomy published by Colin Groves, the [[aye-aye]] was placed in its own infraorder, Chiromyiformes, while the rest of the lemurs were placed in Lemuriformes and the lorisoids in Lorisiformes.{{Sfn|Groves|2005}}

Although it is generally agreed that the aye-aye is the most basal member of the lemur clade, the relationship between the other four families is less clear since they diverged during a narrow 10 to 12&nbsp;million-year window between the Late Eocene (42&nbsp;mya) and into the Oligocene (30&nbsp;mya).{{R|2004YoderYang|2008Horvath}}  Although all studies place Cheirogaleidae and Lepilemuridae as a sister clade to Indriidae and Lemuridae, some suggest that Cheirogaleidae and Lepilemuridae diverged first,{{R|2008Orlando|2012McLain}} while others suggest that Indriidae and Lemuridae were the first to branch off.{{R|2008Horvath}}

