[[File:Lepilemur sahamalazensis c.png|thumb|alt=A sportive lemur (small body, long legs, brown fur, large eyes, and thick, furry tail) clings to the side of a tree, with its head turned towards the camera.|The [[Sahamalaza sportive lemur]] (''Lepilemur sahamalazensis'') was identified as a distinct species in 2006.]]
Lemur taxonomy has changed significantly since the first taxonomic classification of lemurs by Carl Linnaeus in 1758. One of the greatest challenges has been the classification of the aye-aye, which has been a topic of debate up until very recently.{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|pp=85<U+2013>86}} Until [[Richard Owen]] published a definitive anatomical study in 1866, early naturalists were uncertain whether the aye-aye (genus ''Daubentonia'') was a [[primate]], [[rodent]], or [[marsupial]].{{Sfn|Sterling|McCreless|2006|pp=159<U+2013>184}}{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=48<U+2013>161}}{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|pp=205<U+2013>207}} However, the placement of the aye-aye within the order Primates remained problematic until very recently. Based on its anatomy, researchers have found support for classifying the genus ''Daubentonia'' as a specialized [[indriidae|indriid]], a [[Cladistics|sister group]] to all strepsirrhines, and as an indeterminate taxon within the order Primates.{{Sfn|Yoder|2003|pp=1242<U+2013>1247}} Molecular tests have now shown Daubentoniidae is basal to all Lemuriformes,{{Sfn|Yoder|2003|pp=1242<U+2013>1247}}{{R|1996YoderVilgalys}} and in 2008, Russell Mittermeier, Colin Groves, and others ignored addressing higher-level taxonomy by defining lemurs as monophyletic and containing five living families, including Daubentoniidae.{{R|2008MittermeierGroves}}

Relationships among lemur families have also proven to be problematic and have yet to be definitively resolved.{{Sfn|Yoder|2003|pp=1242<U+2013>1247}}  To further complicate the issue, several [[Paleogene]] fossil primates from outside Madagascar, such as ''[[Bugtilemur]]'', have been classified as lemurs.{{R|2001Marivaux}}  However, scientific consensus does not accept these assignments based on genetic evidence,{{Sfn|Yoder|2003|pp=1242<U+2013>1247}}{{R|1996YoderVilgalys}} and therefore it is generally accepted that the Malagasy primates are monophyletic.{{Sfn|Yoder|2003|pp=1242<U+2013>1247}}{{R|2008Horvath|2008Orlando}} Another area of contention is the relationship between the sportive lemurs and the extinct [[koala lemur]]s (Megaladapidae).  Formerly grouped in the same family due to similarities in dentition,{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=224<U+2013>283}} they are no longer considered to be closely related due to genetic studies.{{R|2008Orlando}}{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|pp=115<U+2013>136}}

More taxonomic changes have occurred at the genus level, although these revisions have proven more conclusive, often supported by genetic and molecular analysis. The most noticeable revisions included the gradual split of a broadly defined genus ''Lemur'' into separate genera for the [[ring-tailed lemur]], [[ruffed lemur]]s, and [[True lemur|brown lemur]]s due to a host of morphological differences.{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=209<U+2013>323}}{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|pp=137<U+2013>175}}

Due to several taxonomic revisions by Russell Mittermeier, Colin Groves, and others, the number of recognized lemur species has grown from 33 species and subspecies in 1994 to approximately 100 in 2008.{{R|2007Yoder|2008MittermeierGroves}}{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=85<U+2013>88}} With continuing [[cytogenetics|cytogenetic]] and [[molecular genetics|molecular genetic]] research, as well as ongoing [[field study|field studies]], particularly with [[cryptic species]] such as mouse lemurs, the number of recognized lemur species is likely to keep growing.{{R|2007Yoder}} However, the rapid increase in the number of recognized species has had its critics among taxonomists and lemur researchers. Since classifications ultimately depend on the [[Species#Definitions of species|species concept]] used, [[conservation movement|conservationist]]s often favor definitions that result in the splitting of genetically distinct populations into separate species to gain added environmental protection. Others favor a more thorough analysis.{{R|2007Yoder|2007Tattersall}}
{{-}}

==Anatomy and physiology==
<!-- Coming soon: {{main|Lemur anatomy and physiology}} -->
Lemurs vary greatly in size. They include the smallest primates in the world and, until recently, also included some of the largest. They currently range in size from about 30&nbsp;g (1.1&nbsp;oz) for [[Madame Berthe's mouse lemur]] (''Microcebus berthae'') up to 7<U+2013>9&nbsp;kg (15<U+2013>20&nbsp;lb) for the [[indri]] (''Indri indri'') and [[diademed sifaka]] (''Propithecus diadema'').{{Sfn|Goodman|Ganzhorn|Rakotondravony|2003|pp=1159<U+2013>1186}}{{Sfn|Thalmann|Powzyk|2003|pp=1342<U+2013>1345}} When recently extinct species are considered, the size range extended up to that of a [[gorilla]] at 160<U+2013>200&nbsp;kg (350<U+2013>440&nbsp;lb) for ''[[Archaeoindris fontoynonti]]''.{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|pp=85<U+2013>86}}{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=37<U+2013>51}}

[[File:Varecia variegata foot with toilet-claw.jpg|thumb|right|Close-up of a [[ruffed lemur]]'s foot, showing the [[toilet-claw]] on the second toe and nails on all other toes]]
Like all primates, lemurs have five divergent [[digit (anatomy)|digit]]s with [[nail (anatomy)|nail]]s (in most cases) on their hands and feet. Most lemurs possess a laterally compressed, elongated nail, called a [[toilet-claw]], on the second toe and use it for scratching and grooming.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=48<U+2013>161}}{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=284<U+2013>391}} In addition to the toilet-claw, lemurs share a variety of other traits with other strepsirrhine primates, which include a [[rhinarium]] (or "wet nose"); a fully functional [[vomeronasal organ]], which detects [[pheromone]]s; a [[postorbital bar]] and the lack of [[postorbital septum|postorbital closure]] (a wall of thin bone behind the eye); [[orbit (anatomy)|orbit]]s (bony sockets that enclose the eye) that are not fully facing forward; left and right [[mandible]] (lower jaw) bones that are not fully fused; and a small [[brain-to-body mass ratio]].{{Sfn|Tattersall|2006|pp=3<U+2013>18}}{{Sfn|Rowe|1996|p=13}}

Additional traits shared with other prosimian primates (strepsirrhine primates and [[tarsier]]s) include a bicornuate (two-horned) [[uterus]] and [[placentation|epitheliochorial placentation]].{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=392<U+2013>514}}{{Sfn|Rowe|1996|p=13}} Because their thumbs are only pseudo-opposable, making their movement less independent of the other fingers,{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=284<U+2013>391}} their hands are less than perfect at grasping and manipulating objects.{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=23<U+2013>26}} On their feet, they have a widely abducted [[hallux]] (first toe) which facilitates the grasping of tree limbs.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=48<U+2013>161}} A common misconception is that lemurs have a [[prehensile tail]], a trait found only in [[New World monkey]]s, particularly [[atelidae|atelids]], among primates.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=284<U+2013>391}} Lemurs also rely heavily on their sense of smell, a trait shared with most other mammals and primitive primates, but not with the visually oriented higher primates.{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=23<U+2013>26}} This sense of smell is important in terms of marking territory as well as provide an indication of whether or not another lemur is a viable breeding partner.

Lemurs are a diverse group of primates in terms of morphology and physiology.{{R|2007Yoder}} Some lemurs, such as the [[sportive lemur]]s and [[indriidae|indriid]]s, have longer [[hind limb]]s than [[forelimb]]s, making them excellent [[Jumping|leaper]]s.{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|pp=176<U+2013>204}}{{Sfn|Thalmann|2003|pp=1340<U+2013>1342}}{{Sfn|Thalmann|Ganzhorn|2003|pp=1336<U+2013>1340}} Indriids also have a specialized [[digestive system]] for [[folivore|folivory]], exhibiting enlarged [[salivary gland]]s, a spacious [[stomach]], and an elongated [[caecum]] (lower gut) that facilitates [[fermentation (biochemistry)|fermentation]].{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}}{{Sfn|Preston-Mafham|1991|pp=141<U+2013>188}}{{Sfn|Thalmann|Powzyk|2003|pp=1342<U+2013>1345}}{{Sfn|Nowak|1999|pp=84<U+2013>89}}{{Sfn|Richard|2003|pp=1345<U+2013>1348}} The [[hairy-eared dwarf lemur]] (''Allocebus trichotis'') reportedly has a very long [[tongue]], allowing it to feed on [[nectar]].{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=48<U+2013>161}} Likewise, the [[red-bellied lemur]] (''Eulemur rubriventer'') has a feathery brush-shaped tongue, also uniquely adapted to feed on nectar and pollen.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}} The aye-aye has evolved some traits that are unique among primates, making it stand out among the lemurs. Such traits include continuously growing, rodent-like front teeth for gnawing through wood and hard seeds; a highly mobile, filiform (filament-shaped) middle finger for extracting food from tiny holes; large, [[bat]]-like ears for detecting hollow spaces within trees;{{Sfn|Preston-Mafham|1991|pp=141<U+2013>188}}{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=107<U+2013>148}}{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=48<U+2013>161}}{{Sfn|Sterling|2003|pp=1348<U+2013>1351}} and use of self-generated acoustical cues to forage.{{Sfn|Sterling|McCreless|2006|pp=159<U+2013>184}}

Lemurs are unusual since they have great variability in their social structure, yet generally lack [[sexual dimorphism]] in size and canine tooth morphology.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}}{{Sfn|Rowe|1996|p=27}} However, some species tend towards having larger females,{{Sfn|Sterling|McCreless|2006|pp=159<U+2013>184}} and two species of [[true lemur]] (genus ''Eulemur''), the [[gray-headed lemur]] (''E. albocollaris'') and the [[red lemur]] (''E. rufus''), exhibit size differences in canine teeth.{{Sfn|Overdorff|Johnson|2003|pp=1320<U+2013>1324}} True lemurs show [[sexual dichromatism]] (sexual differences in fur coloration),{{Sfn|Rowe|1996|p=27}} but the difference between the genders varies from strikingly obvious, as in the [[blue-eyed black lemur]] (''E. macaco''), to nearly imperceptible in the case of the [[common brown lemur]] (''E. fulvus'').{{Sfn|Overdorff|Johnson|2003|pp=1320<U+2013>1324}}

[[Cryptic species complex|Crypsis]], or the inability of humans to visually distinguish between two or more distinct species, has recently been discovered among lemurs, particularly within the [[sportive lemur]]s (''Lepilemur'') and [[mouse lemur]]s (''Microcebus''). With sportive lemurs, [[subspecies]] were traditionally defined based on slight morphological differences, but new genetic evidence has supported giving full species status to these regional populations.{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|pp=115<U+2013>136}} In the case of mouse lemurs, the [[gray mouse lemur]] (''M. murinus''), [[golden-brown mouse lemur]] (''M. ravelobensis''), and [[Goodman's mouse lemur]] (''M. lehilahytsara'') were considered the same species until recently, when genetic tests identified them as cryptic species.{{R|2008Braune}}

===Dentition===
