!  style="background:#efefef"| Anthropoid primates
| 0<U+00B0>
| 140<U+2013>160<U+00B0>
| 180<U+2013>190<U+00B0>
|}

Although they lack a fovea, some [[diurnality|diurnal]] lemurs have a [[cone cell|cone]]-rich, although less clustered, [[area centralis]].{{Sfn|Ross|Kay|2004|pp=3<U+2013>41}} This area centralis has a high [[rod cell|rod]]-to-cone cell ratio in many diurnal species studied thus far, whereas diurnal anthropoids have no rod cells in their fovea. Once again, this suggests lower visual acuity in lemurs than in anthropoids.{{Sfn|Kirk|Kay|2004|pp=539<U+2013>602}} Furthermore, the rod-to-cone cell ratio can be variable even among diurnal species. For instance, [[Verreaux's sifaka]] (''Propithecus verreauxi'') and the [[indri]] (''Indri indri'') have only a few large cones scattered along their predominantly rod-dominated retina. The eyes of the ring-tailed lemur contain one cone to five rods. Nocturnal lemurs such as mouse lemurs and [[dwarf lemur]]s, on the other hand, have retinas made up entirely of rod cells.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=392<U+2013>514}}

Since cone cells make [[color vision]] possible, the high prevalence of rod cells in lemur eyes suggest they have not [[Evolution of color vision in primates|evolved color vision]].{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=392<U+2013>514}} The most studied lemur, the ring-tailed lemur, has been shown to have blue-yellow vision, but lacks the ability to distinguish red and green hues.{{Sfn|Jolly|2003|pp=1329<U+2013>1331}} Due to [[polymorphism (biology)|polymorphism]] in [[opsin]] genes, which code for color receptivity, [[trichromacy|trichromatic vision]] may rarely occur in females of a few lemur species, such as [[Coquerel's sifaka]] (''Propithecus coquereli'') and the [[red ruffed lemur]] (''Varecia rubra''). Most lemurs, therefore, are either [[monochromacy|monochromats]] or [[dichromacy|dichromats]].{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=392<U+2013>514}}

[[File:Aye-aye (Daubentonia madagascariensis) 4.jpg|thumb|alt=Cat-sized primate with large, membranous ears, black, coarse fur, long, skinny fingers, and forward-facing eyes climbing along a tree branch; its eyes shining yellow, reflecting back the light from the camera flash|[[Aye-aye]]s exhibit eyeshine because they have a reflective layer of tissue in the eye, called a [[tapetum lucidum]].]]
Most lemurs have retained the [[tapetum lucidum]], a reflective layer of tissue in the eye, which is found in many vertebrates.{{Sfn|Rowe|1996|p=27}} This trait is absent in haplorrhine primates, and its presence further limits the visual acuity in lemurs.{{Sfn|Godfrey|Jungers|Schwartz|2006|pp=41<U+2013>64}}{{Sfn|Kirk|Kay|2004|pp=539<U+2013>602}} The strepsirrhine choroidal tapetum is unique among mammals because it is made up of crystalline [[riboflavin]], and the resulting optical scattering is what limits visual acuity.{{Sfn|Kirk|Kay|2004|pp=539<U+2013>602}}  Although the tapetum is considered to be ubiquitous in lemurs, there appear to be exceptions among true lemurs, such as the black lemur and the common brown lemur, as well as the ruffed lemurs.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=392<U+2013>514}}{{Sfn|Godfrey|Jungers|Schwartz|2006|pp=41<U+2013>64}}{{Sfn|Kirk|Kay|2004|pp=539<U+2013>602}} Since the riboflavins in the tapetum have a tendency to dissolve and vanish when processed for histological investigation, however, the exceptions are still debatable.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=392<U+2013>514}}

Lemurs also have a third eyelid known as a [[nictitating membrane]], whereas most other primates have a lesser developed [[plica semilunaris of the conjunctiva|plica semilunaris]].  The nictitating membrane keeps the [[cornea]] moist and clean by sweeping across the eye.{{Sfn|Osman Hill|1953|p=13}}{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=470<U+2013>471}}

===Metabolism===
Lemurs have low [[basal metabolic rate]]s (BMR), which helps them to conserve energy during the dry season, when water and food are scarce.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}}{{Sfn|Thalmann|Ganzhorn|2003|pp=1336<U+2013>1340}} They can optimize their energy use by lowering their metabolic rate to 20% below the values predicted for mammals of similar body mass.{{Sfn|Schmid|Stephenson|2003|pp=1198<U+2013>1203}} The [[red-tailed sportive lemur]] (''Lepilemur ruficaudatus''), for instance, reportedly has one of the lowest metabolic rates among mammals. Its low metabolic rate may be linked to its generally folivorous diet and relatively small body mass.{{Sfn|Thalmann|Ganzhorn|2003|pp=1336<U+2013>1340}} Lemurs exhibit behavioral adaptations to complement this trait, including sunning behaviors, hunched sitting, group huddling, and nest sharing, in order to reduce heat loss and conserve energy.{{Sfn|Schmid|Stephenson|2003|pp=1198<U+2013>1203}} Dwarf lemurs and mouse lemurs exhibit seasonal cycles of [[dormancy]] to conserve energy.{{Sfn|Schmid|Stephenson|2003|pp=1198<U+2013>1203}} Before dry season, they will accumulate fat in [[white adipose tissue]] located at the base of the tail and hind legs, doubling their weight.{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=89<U+2013>182}}{{Sfn|Nowak|1999|pp=65<U+2013>71}}{{Sfn|Fietz|2003|pp=1307<U+2013>1309}} At the end of the dry season, their body mass may fall to half of what it was prior to the dry season.{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=89<U+2013>182}} Lemurs that do not experience states of dormancy are also able to shut down aspects of their metabolism for energy conservation.{{Sfn|Schmid|Stephenson|2003|pp=1198<U+2013>1203}}

==Behavior==
<!-- Coming soon: {{main|Lemur behavior}} -->
Lemur behavior is as variable as lemur morphology. Differences in diet, social systems, activity patterns, locomotion, communication, predator avoidance tactics, breeding systems, and intelligence levels help define lemur taxa and set individual species apart from the rest. Although trends frequently distinguish the smaller, nocturnal lemurs from the larger, diurnal lemurs, there are often exceptions that help exemplify the unique and diverse nature of these Malagasy primates.

===Diet===
[[File:Microcebus murinus -Artis Zoo, Amsterdam, Netherlands-8c.jpg|thumb|right|alt=A tiny mouse lemur holds a cut piece of fruit in its hands and eats|[[Mouse lemur]]s primarily eat fruit, although their diet also includes insects.]]
Lemur diets are highly variable and demonstrate a high degree of plasticity,{{Sfn|Birkinshaw|Colquhoun|2003|pp=1207<U+2013>1220}} although general trends suggest that the smallest species primarily consume fruit and insects ([[omnivore|omnivory]]), while the larger species are more [[herbivore|herbivorous]], consuming mostly plant material.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}} As with all primates, hungry lemurs might eat anything that is edible, whether or not the item is one of their preferred foods.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=392<U+2013>514}} For instance, the Ring-tailed Lemur eats insects and small [[vertebrate]]s when necessary{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}}{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=209<U+2013>323}} and as a result it is commonly viewed as an opportunistic omnivore.{{Sfn|Cuozzo|Yamashita|2006|pp=67<U+2013>96}} [[Coquerel's giant mouse lemur]] (''Mirza coquereli'') is mostly [[frugivore|frugivorous]], but will consume insect secretions during the dry season.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}}

A common assumption in [[mammalogy]] is that small mammals cannot subsist entirely on plant material and must have a high-calorie diet in order to survive.  As a result, it was thought that the diet of tiny primates must be high in protein-containing insects ([[insectivore|insectivory]]). Research has shown, however, that mouse lemurs, the smallest living primates, consume more fruit than insects, contradicting the popular hypothesis.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=392<U+2013>514}}{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}}

Plant material makes up the majority of most lemur diets. Members of at least 109 of all known plant families in Madagascar (55%) are exploited by lemurs. Since lemurs are primarily arboreal, most of these exploited species are [[woody plant]]s, including [[tree]]s, [[shrub]]s, or [[liana]]s. Only the ring-tailed lemur, the [[bamboo lemur]]s (genus ''Hapalemur''), and the [[black-and-white ruffed lemur]] (''Varecia variegata'') are known to consume [[herb]]s. While Madagascar is rich in [[fern]] diversity, these plants are rarely eaten by lemurs. One possible reason for this is that ferns lack flowers, fruits, and seeds<U+2014>common food items in lemur diets. They also occur close to the ground, while lemurs spend most of their time in the trees. Lastly, ferns have an unpleasant taste due to the high content of [[tannin]]s in their [[frond]]s. Likewise, [[mangrove]]s appear to be rarely exploited by lemurs due to their high tannin content.{{Sfn|Birkinshaw|Colquhoun|2003|pp=1207<U+2013>1220}} Some lemurs appear to have evolved responses against common plant defenses, however, such as tannins and alkaloids.{{Sfn|Powzyk|Mowry|2006|pp=353<U+2013>368}} The [[golden bamboo lemur]] (''Hapalemur aureus''), for instance, eats giant bamboo (''[[Cathariostachys madagascariensis]]''), which contains high levels of [[cyanide]]. This lemur can consume twelve times the typically lethal dose for most mammals on a daily basis; the physiological mechanisms that protect it from cyanide poisoning are unknown.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}} At the [[Duke Lemur Center]] (DLC) in the United States, lemurs that roam the outdoor enclosures have been observed eating [[poison ivy]] (''Taxicodendron radicans''), yet have shown no ill effects.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=284<U+2013>391}}

[[File:Prolemur simus Cedric Girard-Buttoz.jpg|thumb|left|upright|alt=A brown-colored lemur clings to a shaft of giant bamboo while eating a fragment in its hands.|Up to 95% of the [[greater bamboo lemur]]'s diet consists of bamboo.{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=209<U+2013>323}}]]
Many of the larger lemur species consume leaves ([[folivore|folivory]]),{{Sfn|Birkinshaw|Colquhoun|2003|pp=1207<U+2013>1220}} particularly the indriids.{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|pp=176<U+2013>204}} However, some smaller lemurs such as [[sportive lemur]]s (genus ''Lepilemur'') and [[woolly lemur]]s (genus ''Avahi'') also primarily eat leaves, making them the smallest primates that do so.{{Sfn|Thalmann|Ganzhorn|2003|pp=1336<U+2013>1340}} The smallest of the lemurs generally do not eat much leaf matter.{{Sfn|Birkinshaw|Colquhoun|2003|pp=1207<U+2013>1220}} Collectively, lemurs have been documented consuming leaves from at least 82 native plant families and 15 alien plant families. Lemurs tend to be selective in their consumption of the part of the leaf or shoot as well as its age. Often, young leaves are preferred over mature leaves.{{Sfn|Birkinshaw|Colquhoun|2003|pp=1207<U+2013>1220}}

Many lemurs that eat leaves tend to do so during times of fruit scarcity, sometimes suffering weight loss as a result.{{Sfn|Wright|2006|pp=385<U+2013>402}} Most lemur species, including most of the smallest lemurs and excluding some of the indriids, predominantly eat fruit ([[frugivore|frugivory]]) when available. Collectively, lemurs have been documented consuming fruit from at least 86&nbsp;native plant families and 15&nbsp;alien plant families. As with most tropical fruit eaters, the lemur diet is dominated by fruit from ''[[Ficus]]'' (fig) species.{{Sfn|Birkinshaw|Colquhoun|2003|pp=1207<U+2013>1220}} In many anthropoid primates, fruit is a primary source of [[vitamin C]], but unlike anthropoid primates, lemurs (and all strepsirrhines) can synthesize their own vitamin C.{{R|1969Nakajima}} Historically, captive lemur diets high in vitamin C-rich fruits have been thought to cause [[hemosiderosis]], a type of [[iron overload|iron overload disorder]], since vitamin C increases iron absorption. Although lemurs in captivity have been shown to be prone to hemosiderosis, the frequency of the disease varies across institutions and may depend on the diet, husbandry protocols, and genetic stock. Assumptions about the problem need to be tested separately for each species.{{R|2006Williams}} The ring-tailed lemur, for instance, seems to be less prone to the disorder than other lemur species.{{R|2006Glenn}}

Only eight species of lemur are known to be [[seed predation|seed predators]] (granivores), but this may be under-reported since most observations only report fruit consumption and do not investigate whether the seeds are consumed as well. These lemurs include some indriids, such as the [[diademed sifaka]] (''Propithecus diadema''), the [[golden-crowned sifaka]] (''Propithecus tattersalli''), the indri,{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}}{{Sfn|Richard|2003|pp=1345<U+2013>1348}} and the aye-aye. The aye-aye, which specializes in structurally defended resources, can chew through ''[[Canarium]]'' seeds, which are harder than the seeds that [[New World monkey]]s are known to break open.{{Sfn|Sterling|McCreless|2006|pp=159<U+2013>184}} At least 36&nbsp;genera from 23&nbsp;families of plants are targeted by lemur seed predators.{{Sfn|Birkinshaw|Colquhoun|2003|pp=1207<U+2013>1220}}

[[Inflorescence]]s (clusters of flowers) of at least 60&nbsp;plant families are eaten by lemurs ranging in size from the tiny mouse lemurs to the relatively large ruffed lemurs. If the flowers are not exploited, sometimes the nectar is consumed ([[nectarivore|nectarivory]]) along with the pollen ([[palynivore|palynivory]]). At least 24&nbsp;native species from 17&nbsp;plant families are targeted for nectar or pollen consumption.{{Sfn|Birkinshaw|Colquhoun|2003|pp=1207<U+2013>1220}}

Bark and plant exudates such as [[tree sap]] are consumed by a few lemur species. The exploitation of exudates has been reported in 18 plant species and only in the dry regions in the south and west of Madagascar. Only the [[Masoala fork-marked lemur]] (''Phaner furcifer'') and Coquerel's giant mouse lemur regularly consume tree sap. Bark has never been reported as an important food item in lemur diets, but at least four species eat it: the aye-aye, the [[red-tailed sportive lemur]] (''Lepilemur ruficaudatus''), the [[common brown lemur]] (''Eulemur fulvus''), and [[Verreaux's sifaka]] (''Propithecus verreauxi''). Most bark feeding is directly linked to exudate feeding, except for the aye-aye's bark feeding on ''[[Afzelia bijuga]]'' (genus ''[[Afzelia]]'') at [[Nosy Mangabe]] in the northeast.{{Sfn|Birkinshaw|Colquhoun|2003|pp=1207<U+2013>1220}}

Soil consumption ([[geophagy]]) has also been reported and likely helps with [[digestion]], provides minerals and salts, and helps absorb toxins. Sifakas have been observed eating soil from [[termite]] mounds, possibly adding beneficial [[Gut flora|intestinal flora]] to aid the digestion of [[cellulose]] from their folivorous diet.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=284<U+2013>391}}

===Social systems===
Lemurs are social and live in groups that usually include less than 15&nbsp;individuals.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}} Observed [[social organisation|social organization]] patterns include "[[solitary but social]]", "[[Fission-fusion society|fission-fusion]]", "[[pair bond]]s", and "[[multi-male group]]".{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=3<U+2013>37}} Nocturnal lemurs are mostly solitary but social, foraging alone at night but often nesting in groups during the day. The degree of socialization varies by species, gender, location, and season.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=107<U+2013>148}}{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}} In many nocturnal species, for instance, the females, along with their young, will share nests with other females and possibly one male, whose larger [[home range]] happens to overlap one or more female nesting groups. In [[sportive lemur]]s and [[fork-marked lemur]]s, one or two females may share a home range, possibly with a male. In addition to sharing nests, they will also interact vocally or physically with their range-mate while they forage at night.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}} Diurnal lemurs exhibit many of the social systems seen in monkeys and apes,{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}}{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}} living in relatively permanent and cohesive social groups. Multi-male groups are the most common, just as they are in most anthropoid primates. [[True lemur]]s utilize this social system, often living in groups of ten or less. Ruffed lemurs have been shown to live in fission-fusion societies,{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}} and Indri forms pair bonds.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=3<U+2013>37}}

[[File:CHEIROGALEUS-1.JPG|thumb|upright|alt=A small squirrel-like lemur, with a long, slender body and a thick tail, looks over its shoulder from a palm tree.|[[Dwarf lemur]]s are solitary but social, foraging alone but often sleeping in groups.]]
Some lemurs exhibit female [[philopatry]], where females stay within their natal range and the males migrate upon reaching maturity, and in other species both sexes will migrate.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}} In some cases, female philopatry may help explain the evolution of female-bonded multi-male groups, such as those of the ring-tailed lemur, [[Milne-Edwards' sifaka]] (''Propithecus edwardsi''), and the Verreaux's sifaka. Their ancestors may have been more solitary, with females that lived in mother-daughter pairs (or dyads). Over time, these dyads may have allied themselves with other neighboring mother-daughter dyads in order to defend more distributed resources in a wide home range. If this is true, then multi-male groups in lemurs may differ fundamentally in their internal structure from those in [[catarrhini|catarrhine]] primates (Old World monkeys and apes).{{R|1998Jolly}}

The presence of female [[dominance (ethology)|social dominance]] sets lemurs apart from most other primates and mammals;{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}}{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}}{{Sfn|Rowe|1996|p=27}}{{R|2008Dunham}} in most primate societies, males are dominant unless females band together to form coalitions that displace them.{{R|1990Young}} However, many ''Eulemur'' species are exceptions{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}}{{Sfn|Overdorff|Johnson|2003|pp=1320<U+2013>1324}} and the [[greater bamboo lemur]] (''Prolemur simus'') does not exhibit female dominance.{{Sfn|Tan|2006|pp=369<U+2013>382}} When females are dominant within a group, the way they maintain dominance varies. Ring-tailed lemur males act submissively with or without signs of female aggression. Male [[crowned lemur]]s (''Eulemur coronatus''), on the other hand, will only act submissively when females act aggressively towards them. Female aggression is often associated with, but not limited to, feeding.{{R|2002Digby}}

There have been many hypotheses that have attempted to explain why lemurs exhibit female social dominance while other primates with similar social structures do not,{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}}{{R|2008Dunham}} but no consensus has been reached after decades of research. The dominant view in the literature states that female dominance is an advantageous trait given the high costs of reproduction and the scarcity of resources available.{{R|2008Dunham}} Indeed, female dominance has been shown to be linked to increased maternal investment.{{R|1990Young}} However, when reproductive costs and extreme seasonality of resources were compared across primates, other primates demonstrated male dominance under conditions that were similar to or more challenging than those faced by lemurs. In 2008, a new hypothesis revised this model using simple [[game theory]]. It was argued that when two individuals were equally matched in fighting capacity, the one with the most need would win the conflict since it would have the most to lose. Consequently, the female, with higher resource needs for pregnancy, lactation, and maternal care, was more likely to win in resource conflicts with equally sized males. This, however, assumed monomorphism between sexes.{{R|2008Dunham}} The following year, a new hypothesis was proposed to explain monomorphism, stating that because most female lemurs are only sexually receptive for a day or two each year, males can utilize a more passive form of mate guarding: [[Mating plug|copulatory plugs]], which block the female reproductive tract, preventing other males from successfully mating with her, and thus reducing the need for aggression and the evolutionary drive for sexual dimorphism.{{R|2009Dunham}}

[[File:Lemur catta 002.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Two adult Ring-tailed Lemurs lick each other's face while a juvenile moves around on its mother's back.|Social grooming serves many functions for social lemurs.]]
In general, levels of [[agonistic behaviour|agonism]] (or aggression) tend to correlate with relative canine height. The ring-tailed lemur has long, sharp upper canine teeth in both sexes, and it also exhibits high levels of agonism. The Indri, on the other hand, has smaller canines and exhibits lower levels of aggression.{{Sfn|Godfrey|Jungers|Schwartz|2006|pp=41<U+2013>64}} When neighboring groups of the same species defend their territories, the conflict can take the form of ritualized defense. In sifakas, these ritualized combats involve staring, growling, scent-marking, and leaping to occupy certain sections of the tree. The indri defends its home range with ritualized "singing" battles.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}}

Like other primates, lemurs groom socially ([[Social grooming|allogroom]]) to ease tensions and solidify relationships. They groom in greeting, when waking up, when settling in for sleep, between mother and infant, in juvenile relations, and for sexual advances.{{R|1966Jolly}} Unlike anthropoid primates, who part the fur with the hands and pick out particles with the fingers or mouth, lemurs groom with their tongue and scraping with their toothcomb.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}}{{R|1966Jolly}} Despite the differences in technique, lemurs groom with the same frequency and for the same reasons as anthropoids.{{R|1966Jolly}}
{{-}}

===Activity patterns===
The [[Chronobiology|biological rhythm]] can vary from nocturnal in smaller lemurs to diurnal in most larger lemurs. Diurnality is not seen in any other prosimian.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=107<U+2013>148}} [[Cathemeral]]ity, where an animal is active sporadically both day and night, occurs among some of the larger lemurs. Few if any other primates exhibit this sort of activity cycle,{{Sfn|Curtis|2006|pp=133<U+2013>158}} either regularly or irregularly under changing environmental conditions.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}} The most heavily studied cathemeral lemurs are the true lemurs.{{Sfn|Rowe|1996|p=27}}{{Sfn|Johnson|2006|pp=187<U+2013>210}} Although the [[mongoose lemur]] (''E. mongoz'') is the best-documented example, every species in the genus studied has shown some degree of cathemeral behavior,{{Sfn|Overdorff|Johnson|2003|pp=1320<U+2013>1324}} although night activity is often restricted by light availability and moon periodicity.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=392<U+2013>514}} This type of behavior was first documented in the 1960s in true lemur species as well as other [[Lemuridae]] species, such as [[ruffed lemur]]s and [[bamboo lemur]]s. Initially described as "[[crepuscular]]" (active at dawn and dusk), [[anthropologist]] [[Ian Tattersall]] stimulated additional research and coined the new term "cathemeral",{{Sfn|Curtis|2006|pp=133<U+2013>158}} although many non-anthropologists prefer the terms "circadian" or "diel".{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=392<U+2013>514}}

In order to conserve energy and water in their highly seasonal environment,{{Sfn|Schmid|Stephenson|2003|pp=1198<U+2013>1203}}{{Sfn|Fietz|Dausmann|2006|pp=97<U+2013>110}} mouse lemurs and dwarf lemurs exhibit seasonal behavioral cycles of [[dormancy]] where the metabolic rate and body temperature are lowered. They are the only primates known to do so.{{Sfn|Schmid|Stephenson|2003|pp=1198<U+2013>1203}} They accumulate fat reserves in their hind legs and the base of their tail before the dry winter season, when food and water are scarce,{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=89<U+2013>182}}{{Sfn|Nowak|1999|pp=65<U+2013>71}} and can exhibit daily and prolonged [[torpor]] during the dry season. Daily torpor constitutes less than 24 hours of dormancy, whereas prolonged torpor averages two weeks in duration and signals [[hibernation]].{{Sfn|Schmid|Stephenson|2003|pp=1198<U+2013>1203}} Mouse lemurs have been observed experiencing torpor that lasts for several consecutive days, but dwarf lemurs are known to hibernate for six to eight months every year,{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=107<U+2013>148}}{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=89<U+2013>182}}{{Sfn|Fietz|2003|pp=1307<U+2013>1309}} particularly on the west coast of Madagascar.{{Sfn|Fietz|Dausmann|2006|pp=97<U+2013>110}}

Dwarf lemurs are the only primates known to hibernate for extended periods.{{Sfn|Schmid|Stephenson|2003|pp=1198<U+2013>1203}}{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|pp=86<U+2013>114}} Unlike other hibernating mammals from [[Temperateness|temperate regions]], which have to awaken regularly for a few days, dwarf lemurs experience five months of continuous deep hibernation (May through September). Before and after this deep hibernation, there are two months (April and October) of transition, where they will forage on a limited basis to reduce demands on their fat reserves.{{Sfn|Fietz|Dausmann|2006|pp=97<U+2013>110}} Unlike any other hibernating mammal, the body temperature of hibernating dwarf lemurs will fluctuate with the ambient temperature rather than remaining low and stable.{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=89<U+2013>182}}{{Sfn|Fietz|2003|pp=1307<U+2013>1309}}{{Sfn|Fietz|Dausmann|2006|pp=97<U+2013>110}}

Other lemurs that do not exhibit dormancy conserve energy by selecting thermoregulated microhabitats (such as tree holes), sharing nests, and reducing exposed body surfaces, such as by hunched sitting and group huddling. Also, the ring-tailed lemur, ruffed lemurs, and sifakas are commonly seen sunning, thus using solar radiation to warm their bodies instead of [[metabolism|metabolic heat]].{{Sfn|Schmid|Stephenson|2003|pp=1198<U+2013>1203}}

===Locomotion===
[[File:Propithecus verreauxi i.jpg|thumb|right|upright|alt=An upright Coquerel's sifaka hops sideways with its arms at chest height.|[[Sifaka]]s are specially adapted to vertical clinging and leaping, so they must hop sideways to move on the ground.]]
[[Animal locomotion|Locomotor behavior]] in lemurs, both living and extinct, is highly varied and its diversity exceeds that of anthropoids.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}} Locomotor postures and behaviors have included [[vertical clinging and leaping]] (including [[Jumping|saltatory]] behavior), seen in indriids and bamboo lemurs;{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}}{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|pp=176<U+2013>204}} slow ([[loris]]-like) arboreal quadrupedal locomotion, once exhibited by ''[[Mesopropithecus]]'';{{R|2003Godfrey}} fast arboreal quadrupedal locomotion, seen in true lemurs and ruffed lemurs;{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}}{{Sfn|Nowak|1999|pp=71<U+2013>81}} partially terrestrial quadrupedal locomotion, seen in the ring-tailed lemur; highly terrestrial quadrupedal locomotion, once exhibited by [[monkey lemur]]s such as ''[[Hadropithecus]]'';{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}} and [[sloth]]-like suspensory locomotion, once exhibited by many of the [[sloth lemur]]s, such as ''[[Palaeopropithecus]]''.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}}{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}} The [[Lac Alaotra gentle lemur]] (''Hapalemur alaotrensis'') has even been reported to be a good [[Aquatic locomotion|swimmer]].{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}} Sometimes these locomotor types are lumped together into two main groups of lemurs, the vertical clingers and leapers and the arboreal (and occasionally terrestrial) quadrupeds.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=284<U+2013>391}}

The jumping prowess of the indriids have been well documented and are popular among [[ecotourism|ecotourist]]s visiting Madagascar.{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=324<U+2013>403}} Using their long, powerful back legs, they catapult themselves into the air and land in an upright posture on a nearby tree, with both hands and feet tightly gripping the trunk.{{Sfn|Preston-Mafham|1991|pp=141<U+2013>188}} Indriids can leap up to 10&nbsp;m (33&nbsp;ft) rapidly from tree trunk to tree trunk,{{Sfn|Preston-Mafham|1991|pp=141<U+2013>188}}{{Sfn|Nowak|1999|pp=84<U+2013>89}} an ability referred to as "ricochetal leaping".{{Sfn|Powzyk|Mowry|2006|pp=353<U+2013>368}} [[Verreaux's sifaka]] (''Propithecus verreauxi'') manages to do this in the [[Madagascar spiny thickets|spiny forests]] of southern Madagascar. It is unknown how it avoids impaling its palms on the thorn-covered trunks of large plants such as ''[[Alluaudia]]''.{{Sfn|Preston-Mafham|1991|pp=141<U+2013>188}} When distances between trees are too great, sifakas will descend to the ground and cross distances more than 100&nbsp;m (330&nbsp;ft) by standing upright and hopping sideways with the arms held to the side and waving up and down from chest to head height, presumably for balance.{{Sfn|Preston-Mafham|1991|pp=141<U+2013>188}}{{Sfn|Nowak|1999|pp=84<U+2013>89}} This is sometimes described as a "dance-hop".{{Sfn|Preston-Mafham|1991|pp=141<U+2013>188}}

===Communication===
Lemur communication can be transmitted through sound, sight, and smell ([[olfaction]]). The ring-tailed lemur, for instance, uses complex though highly stereotyped behaviors such as [[Territory (animal)|scent-marking]] and [[Ring-tailed lemur vocalizations|vocalizations]].{{Sfn|Jolly|2003|pp=1329<U+2013>1331}} Visual signals are probably the least used by lemurs, since they lack many of the muscles used in common primate [[facial expression]]s.{{R|1959Bolwig}} Given their poor vision, whole-body postures are probably more noticeable. However, the ring-tailed lemur has demonstrated distinct facial expressions including a threat stare, pulled back lips for submission, and pulled back ears along with flared nostrils during scent-marking.{{Sfn|Jolly|2003|pp=1329<U+2013>1331}} This species has also been observed using [[Yawn#Non-human yawning|yawn]]s as threats.{{R|1989Sauther}}{{Sfn|Jolly|1966|p=135}} Their ringed tails also communicate distance, warn off neighboring troops, and help locate troop members.{{Sfn|Jolly|2003|pp=1329<U+2013>1331}} Sifakas are known to exhibit an open-mouth play face{{R|1992Grieser}} as well as a submissive teeth-baring grimace used in agonistic interactions.{{Sfn|Richard|2003|pp=1345<U+2013>1348}}

[[File:Eulemur rubriventer 001.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A red-bellied lemur stands on a branch, rubbing his rump against some smaller branches.|Lemurs use scent-marking to communicate.]]
Olfaction is particularly important to lemurs,{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}} except for the indri, which lacks most common lemur scent glands and has a greatly reduced olfactory region in the brain.{{Sfn|Powzyk|Mowry|2006|pp=353<U+2013>368}} Olfaction can communicate information about age, sex, reproductive status, as well as demarcate the boundaries of a territory. It is most useful for communication between animals that rarely encounter each other.{{Sfn|Sterling|McCreless|2006|pp=159<U+2013>184}} Small, nocturnal lemurs mark their territories with [[urine]], while the larger, diurnal species use scent glands located on various parts of their anatomy. The ring-tailed lemur engages in "stink fights" by rubbing its tail across scent glands on its wrists, and then flicking its tail at other male opponents.  Some lemurs [[defecation|defecate]] in specific areas, otherwise known as [[latrine behavior]]. Although many animals exhibit this behavior, it is a rare trait among primates. Latrine behavior can represent territorial marking and aid in interspecies signaling.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=392<U+2013>514}}

Compared to other mammals, primates in general are very vocal, and lemurs are no exception.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=392<U+2013>514}} Some lemur species have extensive vocal repertoires, including the ring-tailed lemur and ruffed lemurs.{{Sfn|Jolly|2003|pp=1329<U+2013>1331}}{{Sfn|Vasey|2003|pp=1332<U+2013>1336}} Some of the most common calls among lemurs are predator alarm calls. Lemurs not only respond to alarm calls of their own species, but also alarm calls of other species and those of non-predatory birds. The ring-tailed lemur and a few other species have different calls and reactions to specific types of predators.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}} With mating calls, it has been shown that mouse lemurs that cannot be discerned visually respond more strongly to the calls of their own species, particularly when exposed to the calls of other mouse lemurs that they would encounter normally within their home range.{{R|2008Braune}} Lemur calls can also be very loud and carry long distances. Ruffed lemurs use several loud calls that can be heard up to 1&nbsp;km (0.62&nbsp;mi) away on a clear, calm day.{{Sfn|Vasey|2003|pp=1332<U+2013>1336}} The loudest lemur is the indri, whose calls can be heard up to 2&nbsp;km (1.2&nbsp;mi) or more{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=48<U+2013>161}}{{Sfn|Thalmann|Powzyk|2003|pp=1342<U+2013>1345}} and thus communicate more effectively the territorial boundaries over its 34 to 40&nbsp;hectares (0.13 to 0.15&nbsp;sq mi) home range.{{Sfn|Powzyk|Mowry|2006|pp=353<U+2013>368}} Both ruffed lemurs and the indri exhibit contagious calling, where one individual or group starts a loud call and others within the area join in.{{Sfn|Thalmann|Powzyk|2003|pp=1342<U+2013>1345}}{{Sfn|Vasey|2003|pp=1332<U+2013>1336}} The song of the indri can last 45&nbsp;seconds to more than 3&nbsp;minutes and tends to coordinate to form a stable duet comparable to that of [[gibbon]]s.{{Sfn|Thalmann|Powzyk|2003|pp=1342<U+2013>1345}}{{Sfn|Thalmann|Ganzhorn|2003|pp=1336<U+2013>1340}}

[[Somatosensory system|Tactile]] communication (touch) is mostly used by lemurs in the form of grooming, although the ring-tailed lemur also clumps together to sleep (in an order determined by rank), reaches out and touches adjacent members, and cuffs other members. Reaching out and touching another individual in this species has been shown to be a submissive behavior, done by younger or submissive animals towards older and more dominant members of the troop. Allogrooming, however, appears to occur more frequently between higher ranking individuals, a shared trait with other primate species.{{R|1985Hosey}} Unlike anthropoid primates, lemur grooming seems to be more intimate and mutual, often directly reciprocated. Anthropoids, on the other hand, use allogrooming to manage agonistic interactions.{{R|1987Barton}} The ring-tailed lemur is known to be very tactile, spending between 5 and 11% of its time grooming.{{R|1985Hosey}}

{{Sample lemur vocalization}}

===Predator avoidance===
{{ listen
| header    = Lemur alarm calls
| type     = sound
| filename   = Lemur catta--click series & yaps.ogg
| title    = Three types of clicks followed by loud yaps
| alt     = A sequence of clicks which speed up and are then followed by loud yaps
| description = Mammalian predator alert by a ring-tailed lemur
| filename2  = Varecia pulsed squawk1.ogg
| title2    = High-amplitude, pulsed squawks
| alt2     = High-amplitude, pulsed squawks
| description2 = Mammalian predator alert by a ruffed lemur
}}
All lemurs experience some predation pressure.{{Sfn|Goodman|2003|pp=1221<U+2013>1228}} Common defenses against predation include the use of [[alarm call]]s and [[mobbing behavior|predator mobbing]],{{R|2008Eberle}} mostly among diurnal lemurs.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}} The leaping abilities of lemurs may have evolved for predator avoidance rather than for travel, according to a study in [[kinematics]].{{Sfn|Crompton|Sellers|2007|pp=127<U+2013>145}} Nocturnal lemurs are difficult to see and track at night and decrease their visibility by foraging alone. They also try to avoid predators by using concealing sleeping locations, such as nests, tree holes, or dense vegetation,{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}}  Some may also avoid areas frequented by predators by detecting the smell of their feces.{{r|2008S<U+00FC>ndermann}}  and alternating between multiple sleeping locations.{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=89<U+2013>182}} Even torpor and hibernation states among [[cheirogaleidae|cheirogaleids]] may be partly due to high levels of predation.{{Sfn|Goodman|2003|pp=1221<U+2013>1228}} Infants are protected while foraging by either leaving them in the nest or by stashing them in a hidden location, where the infant remains immobile in the absence of the parent.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}}

Diurnal lemurs are visible during the day, so many live in groups, where the increased number of eyes and ears helps aid in predator detection. Diurnal lemurs use and respond to alarm calls, even those of other lemur species and non-predatory birds. The ring-tailed lemur has different calls and reactions to different classes of predators, such as predatory birds, mammals, or snakes.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}} Some lemurs, such as the indri, use [[crypsis]] to camouflage themselves. They are often heard but difficult to see in the trees due to the dappled light, earning them the reputation of being "ghosts of the forest".{{Sfn|Powzyk|Mowry|2006|pp=353<U+2013>368}}

===Reproduction===
Except for the aye-aye and the Lac Alaotra gentle lemur, lemurs are seasonal breeders{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}}{{Sfn|Rowe|1996|p=27}} with very short mating and birth seasons influenced by the highly seasonal availability of resources in their environment. Mating seasons usually last less than three weeks each year,{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}} with the female [[vagina]] opening up only during a few hours or days of her most receptive time of estrus.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=521<U+2013>532}} These narrow windows for reproduction and resource availability appear to relate to their short [[gestation]] periods, rapid maturation, and low basal metabolic rates, as well as the high energy costs of reproduction for females. This may also relate to the relatively high mortality rate among adult females and the higher proportion of adult males in some lemur populations<U+2014>both unusual traits among primates. In both the aye-aye and Lac Alaotra gentle lemur, birth ([[parturition]]) occurs over a six-month period.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}}

Lemurs time their mating and birth seasons so that all [[weaning]] periods are synchronized to match the time of highest food availability.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=521<U+2013>532}}{{Sfn|Wright|2006|pp=385<U+2013>402}} Weaning occurs either before or shortly after the eruption of the first permanent molars in lemurs.{{Sfn|Godfrey|Jungers|Schwartz|2006|pp=41<U+2013>64}} Mouse lemurs are able to fit their entire breeding cycle into the wet season, whereas larger lemurs, such as sifakas, must [[lactation|lactate]] for two months during the dry season.{{Sfn|Wright|2006|pp=385<U+2013>402}} Infant survival in some species, such as Milne-Edwards' sifaka, has been shown to be directly impacted by both environmental conditions and the rank, age, and health of the mother. The breeding season is also affected by geographical location. For example, mouse lemurs give birth between September and October in their native habitat in the [[southern hemisphere]], but from May through June in the captive settings in the [[northern hemisphere]].{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=521<U+2013>532}}

[[File:Avahi laniger 002.jpg|thumb|left|upright|alt=A baby woolly lemur clings to its mother's back as she clings to a tree.|[[Woolly lemur]]s are nocturnal and typically give birth to one offspring, which they carry with them while foraging.]]
Scent factors heavily into lemur reproduction. Scent-marking activity escalates during the [[Estrous cycle|mating season]]. Pheromones may coordinate reproductive timing for females coming into estrus.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=521<U+2013>532}} [[Mating]] can be either [[monogamy|monogamous]] or [[promiscuity|promiscuous]] for both males and females, and mating can include individuals from outside the group.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}}{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}} Monogamous lemurs include the [[red-bellied lemur]] (''Eulemur rubriventer'') and the [[mongoose lemur]] (''E. mongoz''), although the mongoose lemur has been observed mating outside of its pair bond.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}} Monogamy is most common among nocturnal species, although some exhibit scramble competition, sexual suppression of subordinates, or competitions between males that avoid direct fighting.{{Sfn|Godfrey|Jungers|Schwartz|2006|pp=41<U+2013>64}} In mouse lemurs, males utilize [[Mating plug|sperm plugs]], developed enlarged [[Testicle|testes]] during the mating season, and develop size dimorphism (likely due to the enlarged testes). These indicate a mating system known as [[scramble competition polygyny]], where males cannot defend females or the resources that might attract them.{{Sfn|Kappeler|Rasoloarison|2003|pp=1310<U+2013>1315}}

The [[gestation period]] varies within lemurs, ranging from 9 weeks in mouse lemurs and 9<U+2013>10&nbsp;weeks in dwarf lemurs to 18<U+2013>24&nbsp;weeks in other lemurs.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=521<U+2013>532}} The smaller, nocturnal lemurs, such as mouse lemurs, [[giant mouse lemur]]s, and dwarf lemurs, usually give birth to more than one infant, whereas the larger, nocturnal lemurs, such as fork-marked lemurs, sportive lemurs, and the aye-aye usually have one offspring.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=107<U+2013>148}} Dwarf and mouse lemurs have up to four offspring, but both average only two. Ruffed lemurs are the only large, diurnal lemurs to consistently give birth to two or three offspring. All other lemurs have single births. Multiple births in lemurs are normally [[Twin#Fraternal (dizygotic) twins|fraternal]], and are known to occur in every five to six births in species such as the ring-tailed lemur and some ''Eulemur''.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=521<U+2013>532}}

After the offspring are born, lemurs either carry them around or stash them while foraging. When transported, the infants either cling to the mother's fur or are carried in the mouth by the scruff. In some species, such as bamboo lemurs, infants are carried by mouth until they are able to cling to their mother's fur.{{Sfn|Mutschler|Tan|2003|pp=1324<U+2013>1329}} Species that park their offspring include nocturnal species (e.g. mouse lemurs, sportive lemurs, and dwarf lemurs), bamboo lemurs, and ruffed lemurs.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=107<U+2013>148}}{{Sfn|Mutschler|Tan|2003|pp=1324<U+2013>1329}} In the case of the ruffed lemurs, the young are [[altricial]] and the mothers build nests for them, much like the smaller, nocturnal lemur species.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}} Woolly lemurs are unusual for nocturnal lemurs because they live in cohesive family groups and carry their single offspring with them rather than parking them.{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|pp=176<U+2013>204}}{{Sfn|Thalmann|2003|pp=1340<U+2013>1342}} [[Alloparenting]] (multiple or group parenting) has been reported in all lemur families except the sportive lemurs and aye-aye. [[Allonursing]] is also known to occur in several lemur groups.{{R|2007Patel}} Even males have been observed caring for infants in species such as the red-bellied lemur, mongoose lemur,{{Sfn|Overdorff|Johnson|2003|pp=1320<U+2013>1324}} eastern lesser bamboo lemur, silky sifaka,{{R|2007Patel}} fat-tailed dwarf lemur,{{R|2003Fietz}} and ruffed lemurs.{{R|2007Vasey}}

Yet another trait that sets most lemurs apart from anthropoid primates is their long lifespan together with their high infant mortality.{{Sfn|Wright|2006|pp=385<U+2013>402}} Many lemurs, including the ring-tailed lemur, have adapted to a highly seasonal environment, which has affected their birthrate, maturation, and twinning rate ([[r/K selection theory|r-selection]]). This helps them to recover rapidly from a population crash.{{Sfn|Jolly|2003|pp=1329<U+2013>1331}} In captivity, lemurs can live twice as long as they do in the wild, benefiting from consistent nutrition that meets their dietary requirements, medical advancements, and improved understanding of their housing requirements. In 1960, it was thought that lemurs could live between 23 and 25 years. We now know that the larger species can live for more than 30 years without showing signs of aging ([[senescence]]) and still be capable of reproduction.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=521<U+2013>532}}

===Cognitive abilities and tool use===
Lemurs have traditionally been regarded as being less intelligent than anthropoid primates,{{r|1976Ehrlich_et_al}} with [[monkey]]s and apes often described as having more cunning, guile, and deceptiveness.{{Sfn|Preston-Mafham|1991|pp=141<U+2013>188}} Many lemur species, such as sifakas and the ring-tailed lemur, have scored lower on tests designed for monkeys while performing as well as monkeys on other tests.{{Sfn|Preston-Mafham|1991|pp=141<U+2013>188}}{{R|1966Jolly}} These comparisons may not be fair since lemurs prefer to manipulate objects with their mouths (rather than their hands) and only take interest in objects when in captivity.{{R|1966Jolly}} Recent studies have shown that lemurs exhibit levels of technical intelligence on par with many other primates, although they manipulate objects less often.{{Sfn|Fichtel|Kappeler|2010|p=413}} [[Tool use by animals|Tool use]] has not been witnessed by lemurs in the wild, although in captivity the common brown lemur and the ring-tailed lemur have been demonstrated to be able to understand and use tools.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=392<U+2013>514}}

A few lemurs have been noted to have relatively large brains. The extinct ''Hadropithecus'' was as large as a large male [[baboon]] and had a comparably sized brain, giving it the largest brain size relative to body size among all prosimians.{{R|ScienceDaily_29Jul08}} The aye-aye also has a large brain-to-body ratio, which may indicate a higher level of intelligence.{{Sfn|Rowe|1996|p=27}} However, despite having a built-in tool in the form of its thin, elongated middle finger, which it uses to fish for insect grubs, the aye-aye has tested poorly in the use of extraneous tools.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=392<U+2013>514}}

==Ecology==
<!-- Coming soon: {{main|Lemur ecology}} -->
:''See above: [[#Diet|Diet]], [[#Metabolism|Metabolism]], [[#Activity patterns|Activity patterns]], and [[#Locomotion|Locomotion]]''
Madagascar not only contains two radically different [[climate|climatic zone]]s, the rainforests of the east and the dry regions of the west,{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}} but also swings from extended drought to [[cyclone]]-generated floods.{{Sfn|Jolly|Sussman|2006|pp=19<U+2013>40}} These climatic and geographical challenges, along with poor soils, low plant productivity, wide ranges of [[ecosystem]] complexity, and a lack of regularly fruiting trees (such as [[Ficus|fig trees]]) have driven the evolution of lemurs' immense morphological and behavioral diversity.{{Sfn|Gould|Sauther|2006|pp=vii<U+2013>xiii}}{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}}{{Sfn|Godfrey|Jungers|Schwartz|2006|pp=41<U+2013>64}}{{Sfn|Wright|2006|pp=385<U+2013>402}} Their survival has required the ability to endure the persistent extremes, not yearly averages.{{Sfn|Jolly|Sussman|2006|pp=19<U+2013>40}}

{{Multiple image|direction=vertical|align=right|image1=Cryptoprocta Ferox.JPG|image2=Polyboroides radiatus.jpg|width=200|caption2=The [[Fossa (animal)|fossa]] (above) and the [[Madagascar Harrier-hawk|Madagascar harrier-hawk]] (below) are predators of many lemur species.{{Sfn|Goodman|2003|pp=1221<U+2013>1228}}|alt1=A cat-like predator with a long, slender body stands on a rock.|alt2=A gray-feathered hawk with red face and a striped underside stands perched on a branch, looking to its right.}}
Lemurs have either presently or formerly filled the [[ecological niche]]s normally occupied by monkeys, squirrels, [[woodpecker]]s, and grazing [[ungulate]]s.{{Sfn|Preston-Mafham|1991|pp=141<U+2013>188}}  With the diversity of adaptations for specific ecological niches, habitat selections among lemur families and some genera are often very distinct, thus minimizing [[competition (biology)|competition]].{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}} In nocturnal lemurs from the more seasonal forests in the west, up to five species can coexist during the wet season due to high food abundance. However, to endure the extreme dry season, three of the five species utilize different dietary patterns and their underlying physiological traits to allow them to coexist: fork-marked lemurs feed on tree gum, sportive lemurs feed on leaves, and giant mouse lemurs sometimes feed on insect secretions. The other two species, the gray mouse lemur and the fat-tailed dwarf lemur (''Cheirogaleus medius''), avoid competition through reduced activity. The gray mouse lemur uses bouts of torpor, while the fat-tailed dwarf lemur hibernates completely.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=107<U+2013>148}} Similarly, on the east coast entire genera focus on specific food to avoid too much niche overlap. True lemurs and ruffed lemurs are frugivorous, indriids are folivorous, and bamboo lemurs specialize in bamboo and other grasses. Once again, seasonal dietary differences as well as subtle differences in [[substrate (biology)|substrate]] preferences, [[Tropical rainforest#Layers|forest strata]] used, activity cycle, and social organization enable lemur species to coexist, although this time the species are more closely related and have similar niches.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}} A classic example involves [[Niche differentiation|resource partitioning]] between three species of bamboo lemur that live in close proximity in small forested areas: the golden bamboo lemur, the greater bamboo lemur, and the [[eastern lesser bamboo lemur]] (''Hapalemur griseus''). Each utilizes either different species of bamboo, different parts of the plant, or different layers in the forest.{{Sfn|Preston-Mafham|1991|pp=141<U+2013>188}}{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=224<U+2013>283}} Nutrient and toxin content (such as cyanide) help regulate food selection,{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}} though seasonal food preferences are also known to play a role.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=224<U+2013>283}}

Dietary regimes of lemurs include [[folivore|folivory]], [[frugivore|frugivory]], and [[omnivore|omnivory]], with some being highly adaptable while others specialize on foods such as plant exudates (tree gum) and bamboo.{{R|2009Thalmann}}  In some cases, lemur feeding patterns directly benefit the native plant life. When lemurs exploit nectar, they may act as pollinators as long as the functional parts of the flower are not damaged.{{Sfn|Birkinshaw|Colquhoun|2003|pp=1207<U+2013>1220}} In fact, several unrelated Malagasy flowering plants demonstrate lemur-specific pollination traits, and studies indicate that some diurnal species, such as the red-bellied lemur and the ruffed lemurs, act as major pollinators.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}} Two examples of plant species that rely on lemurs for pollination include traveller's palm (''[[Ravenala madagascariensis]]''){{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|pp=137<U+2013>175}} and a species of [[legume]]-like liana, ''[[Strongylodon|Strongylodon cravieniae]]''.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}} [[Seed dispersal]] is another service lemurs provide. After passing through the lemur gut, tree and vine seeds exhibit lower mortality and [[germination|germinate]] faster.{{Sfn|Wright|2006|pp=385<U+2013>402}} Latrine behavior exhibited by some lemurs may help improve soil quality and facilitate seed dispersal.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=392<U+2013>514}} Because of their importance in maintaining a healthy forest, frugivorous lemurs may qualify as [[keystone species|keystone mutualists]].{{Sfn|Wright|2006|pp=385<U+2013>402}}

All lemurs, particularly the smaller species, are affected by predation{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=107<U+2013>148}}{{Sfn|Goodman|2003|pp=1221<U+2013>1228}} and they are important prey items for predators.{{Sfn|Kappeler|Rasoloarison|2003|pp=1310<U+2013>1315}} Humans are the most significant predator of diurnal lemurs, despite [[taboo]]s that occasionally forbid the hunting and eating of certain lemur species.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}} Other predators include native [[eupleridae|euplerids]], such as the [[Fossa (animal)|fossa]], [[feral cat]]s, [[dog|domestic dogs]], [[snake]]s, diurnal [[bird of prey|birds of prey]], [[owl]]s, and [[crocodile]]s. Extinct giant eagles, including one or two species from the genus ''[[Aquila (genus)|Aquila]]'' and the giant [[Malagasy Crowned Eagle|Malagasy crowned eagle]] (''Stephanoaetus mahery''), as well as the giant fossa (''[[Cryptoprocta spelea]]''), previously also preyed on lemurs, perhaps including the giant subfossil lemurs or their subadult offspring.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=107<U+2013>148}}{{Sfn|Goodman|2003|pp=1221<U+2013>1228}} The existence of these extinct giants suggests that predator-prey interactions involving lemurs were more complex than they are today.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}} Today, predator size only restricts owls to the smaller lemurs, usually 100&nbsp;g (3.5&nbsp;oz) or less, while the larger lemurs fall victim to the larger diurnal birds of prey, such as the [[Madagascar Harrier-hawk|Madagascar harrier-hawk]] (''Polyboroides radiatus'') and the [[Madagascar Buzzard|Madagascar buzzard]] (''Buteo brachypterus'').{{Sfn|Goodman|2003|pp=1221<U+2013>1228}}

==Research==
<!-- Coming soon: {{main|Lemur research}} -->
Similarities that lemurs share with anthropoid primates, such as diet and social organization, along with their own unique traits, have made lemurs the most heavily studied of all mammal groups on Madagascar.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}}{{Sfn|Goodman|Ganzhorn|Rakotondravony|2003|pp=1159<U+2013>1186}} Research often focuses on the link between ecology and social organization, but also on their behavior and [[morphophysiology]] (the study of anatomy in relation to function).{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}} Studies of their life-history traits, behavior and ecology help understanding of primate evolution, since they are thought to share similarities with ancestral primates.

Lemurs have been the focus of [[monographic series]], action plans, field guides, and classic works in ethology.{{Sfn|Goodman|Ganzhorn|Rakotondravony|2003|pp=1159<U+2013>1186}} However, few species have been thoroughly studied to date, and most research has been preliminary and restricted to a single locality.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}} Only recently have numerous scientific papers been published to explain the basic aspects of behavior and ecology of poorly known species. [[Field study|Field studies]] have given insights on [[population dynamics]] and [[evolutionary ecology]] of most genera and many species.{{Sfn|Goodman|Ganzhorn|Rakotondravony|2003|pp=1159<U+2013>1186}} Long-term research focused on identified individuals is in its infancy and has only been started for a few populations. However, learning opportunities are dwindling as habitat destruction and other factors threaten the existence of lemur populations across the island.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}}

[[File:Berenty 001.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A dirt road runs under a decorated, arching sign demarcating the Berenty Private Reserve.|[[Berenty Private Reserve]] in southern Madagascar is both a popular tourist destination and research location. [[Alison Jolly]] began her research here in 1962.]]
Lemurs are mentioned in sailors' voyage logs as far back as 1608 and in 1658 that at least seven lemur species were described in detail by the French merchant, [[<U+00C9>tienne de Flacourt]], who may also have been the only westerner to see and chronicle the existence of a giant (now extinct) lemur, which he called the ''[[Subfossil lemur#Lingering populations|tretretretre]]''. Around 1703 merchants and sailors began bringing lemurs back to Europe, at which time [[James Petiver]], an apothecary in London, described and illustrated the mongoose lemur. Starting in 1751, the London illustrator [[George Edwards (naturalist)|George Edwards]] began describing and illustrating some lemur species, of which a few were included in various editions of ''[[Systema Naturae]]'' by Carl Linnaeus. In the 1760s and 1770s, French naturalists [[Georges-Louis Leclerc, Comte de Buffon]] and [[Louis-Jean-Marie Daubenton]] began describing the anatomy of several lemur species. The first traveling naturalist to comment on lemurs was [[Philibert Commer<U+00E7>on]] in 1771, although it was [[Pierre Sonnerat]] who recorded a greater variety of lemur species during his travels.{{Sfn|Jolly|Sussman|2006|pp=19<U+2013>40}}{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=27<U+2013>36}}

During the 19th century, there was an explosion of new lemur descriptions and names, which later took decades to sort out. During this time, professional collectors gathered specimens for [[museum]]s, [[menagerie]]s, and [[Cabinet of curiosities|cabinets]]. Some of the major collectors were [[Johannes Hildebrandt]] and [[Charles Immanuel Forsyth Major]]. From these collections, as well as increasing observations of lemurs in their natural habitats, museum [[systematics|systematists]] including [[Albert G<U+00FC>nther]] and [[John Edward Gray]] continued to contribute new names for new lemur species. However, the most notable contributions from this century includes the work of [[Alfred Grandidier]], a naturalist and explorer who devoted himself to the study of Madagascar's natural history and local people. With the help of [[Alphonse Milne-Edwards]], most of the diurnal lemurs were illustrated at this time. However, lemur taxonomic nomenclature took its modern form in the 1920s and 1930s, being standardized by [[Ernst Schwarz]] in 1931.{{Sfn|Jolly|Sussman|2006|pp=19<U+2013>40}}{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=27<U+2013>36}}

Although lemur taxonomy had developed, it was not until the 1950s and 1960s that the in-situ (or on-site) study of lemur behavior and ecology began to blossom. [[Jean-Jacques Petter]] and [[Arlette Petter-Rousseaux]] toured Madagascar in 1956 and 1957, surveying many of its lemur species and making important observations about their social groupings and reproduction. In 1960, the year of Madagascar's independence, [[David Attenborough]] introduced lemurs to the West with a commercial film. Under the guidance of [[John Buettner-Janusch]], who founded the [[Duke Lemur Center]] in 1966, [[Alison Jolly]] traveled to Madagascar in 1962 to study the diet and social behavior of the ring-tailed lemur and Verreaux's sifaka at [[Berenty Private Reserve]]. The Petters and Jolly spawned a new era of interest in lemur ecology and behavior and were shortly followed by anthropologists such as [[Alison Richard]], [[Robert Sussman]], [[Ian Tattersall]], and many others. Following the political turmoil of the mid-1970s and Madagascar's revolution, field studies resumed in the 1980s, thanks in part to the renewed involvement of the Duke Lemur Center under the direction of [[Elwyn Simons]] and the conservation efforts of [[Patricia Wright]].{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}}{{Sfn|Jolly|Sussman|2006|pp=19<U+2013>40}}{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=27<U+2013>36}} In the decades that followed, huge strides have been made in lemur studies and many new species have been discovered.{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|pp=85<U+2013>86}}

Ex situ research (or off-site research) is also popular among researchers looking to answer questions that are difficult to test in the field. For example, efforts to [[Full genome sequencing|sequence the genome]] of the gray mouse lemur will help researchers understand which genetic traits set primates apart from other mammals and will ultimately help understand what genomic traits set humans apart from other primates.{{R|2007Yoder}} One of the foremost lemur research facilities is the Duke Lemur Center (DLC) in [[Durham, North Carolina]]. It maintains the largest captive lemur population outside of Madagascar, which it maintains for non-invasive research and [[captive breeding]].{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=52<U+2013>84}} Many important research projects have been carried out there, including studies of lemur vocalizations,{{R|1993Macedonia}} basic locomotor research,{{R|1990Tilden}} the [[kinematics]] of bipedalism,{{R|2007Wunderlich}} the effects of social complexity transitive reasoning,{{R|2008MacLean}} and cognition studies involving a lemur's ability to organize and retrieve sequences from memory.{{R|2007Merritt}} Other facilities, such as the [[Lemur Conservation Foundation]], located near [[Myakka City, Florida]], have also hosted research projects, such as one that looked at lemurs' ability to preferentially select tools based on functional qualities.{{R|2005Santos}}

==Conservation==
<!-- Coming soon: {{main|Lemur conservation}} -->
{{Multiple image|direction=vertical|align=right|image1=Madagascar spiny forest destruction 001.jpg|image2=Charcoal and firewood sale 001.jpg|width=225|caption2=Lemurs in the [[Madagascar spiny thickets|spiny forests]] of Madagascar are threatened by deforestation for the creation of farmland and pasture (above) as well as firewood and charcoal production (below) for cooking fuel.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}}||Spiny forest destruction in southern Madagascar, showing trees and brush cut down and lying on the ground|Stacks of bundled firewood and bagged charcoal for sale along the roadside}}
Lemurs are threatened by a host of environmental problems, including [[deforestation]], hunting for [[bushmeat]], live capture for the [[Pet trade#Illegal wildlife trade|exotic pet trade]],{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=15<U+2013>17}} and climate change.{{Sfn|Wright|2006|pp=385<U+2013>402}}  All species are listed by [[CITES]] on [[CITES#Appendix I|Appendix I]], which prohibits trade of specimens or parts, except for scientific purposes.{{Sfn|Harcourt|1990|pp=7<U+2013>13}} As of 2005, the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN) listed 16% of all lemur species as [[Critically Endangered]], 23% as [[Endangered species|Endangered]], 25% as [[Vulnerable species|Vulnerable]], 28% as "Data Deficient", and only 8% as [[Least Concern]].{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=52<U+2013>84}} Over the next five years, at least 28&nbsp;species were newly identified, none of which have had their conservation status assessed.{{R|2008MittermeierGroves}} Many are likely to be considered [[threatened species|threatened]] since the new lemur species that have been described recently are typically confined to small regions.{{Sfn|Mittermeier|Konstant|Rylands|2003|pp=1538<U+2013>1543}} Given the rate of continued [[habitat destruction]], undiscovered species could go extinct before being identified.{{Sfn|Goodman|Ganzhorn|Rakotondravony|2003|pp=1159<U+2013>1186}} Since the arrival of humans on the island approximately 2000&nbsp;years ago, all endemic Malagasy vertebrates over 10&nbsp;kg (22&nbsp;lb) have disappeared,{{Sfn|Burney|2003|pp=47<U+2013>51}} including 17&nbsp;species, 8&nbsp;genera, and 3&nbsp;families of lemurs.{{R|2009Gommery}}{{Sfn|Godfrey|Jungers|2003|pp=1247<U+2013>1252}} The [[IUCN Species Survival Commission]] (IUCN/SSC), the [[International Primatological Society]] (IPS), and [[Conservation International]] (CI) have included as many as five lemurs in their biennial "[[The World's 25 Most Endangered Primates|Top 25 Most Endangered Primates]]". The 2008<U+2013>2010 list includes the greater bamboo lemur, [[gray-headed lemur]] (''Eulemur cinereiceps''), [[blue-eyed black lemur]] (''Eulemur flavifrons''), [[northern sportive lemur]] (''Lepilemur septentrionalis''), and silky sifaka.{{R|2009Mittermeier}}  In 2012, an assessment by the [[IUCN Species Survival Commission#Primate Specialist Group|Primate Specialist Group]] of the [[International Union for the Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN) concluded that 90% of the then 103&nbsp;described species of lemur should be listed as [[Threatened species|Threatened]] on the [[IUCN Red List]],{{r|BBC_13Jul12}} making lemurs the most endangered group of mammals.{{r|LiveScience_13Jul12}}  The IUCN reiterated its concern in 2013, noting that 90% of all lemur species could be extinct within 20 to 25&nbsp;years unless a $7&nbsp;million USD 3-year conservation plan aimed at helping local communities can be implemented.{{r|Telegraph_19Aug13|IBT_21Aug13}} 

Madagascar is one of the poorest countries in the world,{{R|2009eStandardsForum|ScienceDaily_14Jun08}} with a high [[population growth]] rate of 2.5%&nbsp;per year and nearly 70% of the population living in poverty.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}}{{R|2009eStandardsForum}} The country is also burdened with high levels of debt and limited resources.{{R|ScienceDaily_14Jun08}} These socioeconomic issues have complicated conservation efforts, even though the island of Madagascar has been recognized by IUCN/SSC as a critical primate region for over 20&nbsp;years.{{Sfn|Mittermeier|Konstant|Rylands|2003|pp=1538<U+2013>1543}} Due to its relatively small land area<U+2014>587,045&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> (226,659&nbsp;sq mi)<U+2014>compared to other high-priority [[biodiversity]] regions and its high levels of [[endemism]], the country is considered one of the world's most important [[biodiversity hotspot]]s, with lemur conservation being a high priority.{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=52<U+2013>84}}{{Sfn|Mittermeier|Konstant|Rylands|2003|pp=1538<U+2013>1543}} Despite the added emphasis for conservation, there is no indication that the extinctions that began with the arrival of humans have come to an end.{{Sfn|Burney|2003|pp=47<U+2013>51}}

===Threats in the wild===
The greatest concern facing lemur populations is habitat destruction and degradation.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}}{{Sfn|Harcourt|1990|pp=7<U+2013>13}} Deforestation takes the form of local subsistence use, such as [[slash and burn]] agriculture (referred to as ''tavy'' in Malagasy), the creation of [[pasture]] for cattle through burning, and legal and illegal gathering of wood for [[firewood]] or [[charcoal]] production; commercial [[mining]]; and the [[Illegal logging in Madagascar|illegal logging]] of precious [[hardwood]]s for foreign markets.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}}{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=15<U+2013>17}} After centuries of unsustainable use, as well as rapidly escalating forest destruction since 1950,{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=52<U+2013>84}} less than 60,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> (23,000&nbsp;sq mi) or 10% of Madagascar's land area remains forested. Only 17,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> (6,600&nbsp;sq mi) or 3% of the island's land area is protected and due to dire economic conditions and [[2009 Malagasy political crisis|political instability]], most of the protected areas are ineffectively managed and defended.{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=15<U+2013>17}}{{Sfn|Mittermeier|Konstant|Rylands|2003|pp=1538<U+2013>1543}} Some protected areas were set aside because they were naturally protected by their remote, isolated location, often on steep cliffs. Other areas, such as the [[Madagascar dry deciduous forests|dry forests]] and [[Madagascar spiny thickets|spiny forests]] of the west and south, receive little protection and are in serious danger of being destroyed.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=257<U+2013>269}}

Some species may be in risk of extinction even without complete deforestation, such as ruffed lemurs, which are very sensitive to habitat disturbance.{{Sfn|Goodman|Ganzhorn|Rakotondravony|2003|pp=1159<U+2013>1186}} If large fruit trees are removed, the forest may sustain fewer individuals of a species and their reproductive success may be affected for years.{{Sfn|Wright|2006|pp=385<U+2013>402}} Small populations may be able to persist in isolated forest fragments for 20 to 40&nbsp;years due to long generation times, but in the long term, such populations may not be viable.{{Sfn|Ganzhorn|Goodman|Dehgan|2003|pp=1228<U+2013>1234}} Small, isolated populations also risk [[Local extinction|extirpation]] by natural disasters and disease outbreaks ([[epizootic]]s). Two diseases that are lethal to lemurs and could severely impact isolated lemur populations are [[toxoplasmosis]], which is spread by feral cats, and the [[herpes simplex virus]] carried by humans.{{Sfn|Junge|Sauther|2006|pp=423<U+2013>440}}

[[File:Lemur poaching 004.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Two Malagasy hunters stand near a stream, one holding a gun, the other holding a lemur with a white head.|Lemurs, such as this [[white-headed lemur]], are killed for [[bushmeat]] in Madagascar.]]
Climate change and weather-related natural disasters also threaten lemur survival. For the last 1000 years, western and highland regions have been growing significantly drier, but in the past few decades, severe drought has become much more frequent. There are indications that deforestation and forest fragmentation are accelerating this gradual desiccation.{{Sfn|Wright|2006|pp=385<U+2013>402}} The effects of drought are even felt in the rainforests. As annual rainfall decreases, the larger trees that make up the high [[canopy (biology)|canopy]] suffer increased mortality, failure to fruit, and decreased production of new leaves, which folivorous lemurs prefer. Cyclones can defoliate an area, knock down canopy trees, and create landslides and flooding. This can leave lemur populations without fruit or leaves until the following spring, requiring them to subsist on crisis foods, such as [[epiphyte]]s.{{Sfn|Ratsimbazafy|2006|pp=403<U+2013>422}}

Lemurs are hunted for food by the local Malagasy, either for local subsistence{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|pp=85<U+2013>86}}{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=15<U+2013>17}} or to supply a luxury meat market in the larger cities.{{R|2010Butler}} Most rural Malagasy do not understand what "endangered" means, nor do they know that hunting lemurs is illegal or that lemurs are found only in Madagascar.{{Sfn|Simons|1997|pp=142<U+2013>166}} Many Malagasy have taboo, or ''fady'', about hunting and eating lemurs, but this does not prevent hunting in many regions.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}} Even though hunting has been a threat to lemur populations in the past, it has recently become a more serious threat as socioeconomic conditions deteriorate.{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=15<U+2013>17}} Economic hardships have caused people to move around the country in search of employment, leading local traditions to break down.{{Sfn|Goodman|Ganzhorn|Rakotondravony|2003|pp=1159<U+2013>1186}}{{Sfn|Harcourt|1990|pp=7<U+2013>13}}{{Sfn|Simons|1997|pp=142<U+2013>166}} Drought and famine can also relax the ''fady'' that protect lemurs.{{Sfn|Goodman|Ganzhorn|Rakotondravony|2003|pp=1159<U+2013>1186}} Larger species, such as sifakas and ruffed lemurs, are common targets, but smaller species are also hunted or accidentally caught in snares intended for larger prey.{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|pp=85<U+2013>86}}{{Sfn|Harcourt|1990|pp=7<U+2013>13}} Experienced, organized hunting parties using firearms, slings and blowguns can kill as many as eight to twenty lemurs in one trip. Organized hunting parties and lemur traps can be found in both non-protected areas and remote corners of protected areas.{{Sfn|Goodman|Ganzhorn|Rakotondravony|2003|pp=1159<U+2013>1186}} National parks and other protected areas are not adequately protected by law enforcement agencies.{{Sfn|Simons|1997|pp=142<U+2013>166}} Often, there are too few park rangers to cover a large area, and sometimes terrain within the park is too rugged to check regularly.{{R|2009Schuurman}}

Although not as significant as deforestation and hunting, some lemurs, such as crowned lemurs and other species that have successfully been kept in captivity, are occasionally kept as [[exotic pet]]s by Malagasy people.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=48<U+2013>161}}{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=52<U+2013>84}} Bamboo lemurs are also kept as pets,{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=52<U+2013>84}} although they only survive for up to two months.{{Sfn|Rowe|1996|p=46}} Live capture for the exotic pet trade in wealthier countries is not normally considered a threat due to strict regulations controlling their export.{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=52<U+2013>84}}{{Sfn|Harcourt|1990|pp=7<U+2013>13}}

===Conservation efforts===
[[File:Illegal export of rosewood 002.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Eight rosewood logs lying at the riverside with nearby workers, a truck, and a cart|[[Rosewood]] is [[Illegal logging in Madagascar|logged illegally]] from national parks, such as [[Marojejy National Park|Marojejy]].]]
Lemurs have drawn much attention to Madagascar and its endangered species. In this capacity, they act as [[flagship species]],{{Sfn|Goodman|Ganzhorn|Rakotondravony|2003|pp=1159<U+2013>1186}}{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=52<U+2013>84}} the most notable of which is the ring-tailed lemur, which is considered an icon of the country.{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|pp=137<U+2013>175}} The presence of lemurs in national parks helps drive [[ecotourism]],{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=52<U+2013>84}} which especially helps local communities living in the vicinity of the national parks, since it offers employment opportunities and the community receives half of the park entrance fees.  In the case of [[Ranomafana National Park]], job opportunities and other revenue from long-term research can rival that of ecotourism.{{Sfn|Wright|Andriamihaja|2003|pp=1485<U+2013>1488}}

Starting in 1927, the [[Politics of Madagascar|Malagasy government]] has declared all lemurs as "protected"{{Sfn|Sterling|2003|pp=1348<U+2013>1351}} by establishing protected areas that are now classified under three categories: National Parks (Parcs Nationaux), Strict Nature Reserves (R<U+00E9>serves Naturelles Int<U+00E9>grales), and Special Reserves (R<U+00E9>serves Sp<U+00E9>ciales). There are currently 18&nbsp;national parks, 5&nbsp;strict nature reserves, and 22&nbsp;special reserves, as well as several other small private reserves, such as [[Berenty Private Reserve|Berenty Reserve]] and [[Sainte Luce Private Reserve]], both near [[T<U+00F4>lanaro|Fort Dauphin]].{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=52<U+2013>84}} All protected areas, excluding the private reserves, comprise approximately 3% of the land surface of Madagascar and are managed by [[Madagascar National Parks]], formerly known as l'Association Nationale pour la Gestion des Aires Prot<U+00E9>g<U+00E9>es (ANGAP), as well as other [[non-governmental organization]]s (NGOs), including [[Conservation International]] (CI), the [[Wildlife Conservation Society]] (WCS), and the [[World Wide Fund for Nature]] (WWF).{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=52<U+2013>84}}{{Sfn|Mittermeier|Konstant|Rylands|2003|pp=1538<U+2013>1543}} Most lemur species are covered by this network of protected areas, and a few species can be found in multiple parks or reserves.{{Sfn|Mittermeier|Konstant|Rylands|2003|pp=1538<U+2013>1543}}

Conservation is also facilitated by the [[Madagascar Fauna Group]] (MFG), an association of nearly 40&nbsp;zoos and related organizations, including the Duke Lemur Center, the [[Durrell Wildlife Conservation Trust]], and the [[Saint Louis Zoological Park]]. This international NGO supports Madagascar's [[Parc Ivoloina]], helps protect [[Betampona Reserve]] and other protected areas, and promotes field research, breeding programs, conservation planning, and education in zoos.{{Sfn|Sargent|Anderson|2003|pp=1543<U+2013>1545}} One of their major projects involved the release of captive black-and-white ruffed lemurs, designed to help restock the dwindling population within Betampona Reserve.{{Sfn|Sargent|Anderson|2003|pp=1543<U+2013>1545}}{{Sfn|Britt|Iambana|Welch|Katz|2003|pp=1545<U+2013>1551}}

[[File:Rice paddies in Madagascar 001.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A landscape showing a lush, green rice paddy surrounded by barren, dry hills|Rice paddies have gradually replaced lemur habitat, particularly in the central part of the island.]]
[[Habitat corridor]]s are needed for linking these protected areas so that small populations are not isolated.{{Sfn|Mittermeier|Konstant|Rylands|2003|pp=1538<U+2013>1543}} In {{Nowrap|September 2003}} in [[Durban]], South Africa, Madagascar's former president [[Marc Ravalomanana]] promised to triple the size of the island's protected areas in five years.{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=15<U+2013>17}} This became known as the "Durban Vision".{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=52<U+2013>84}} In June&nbsp;2007, the [[World Heritage Committee]] included a sizable portion of Madagascar's eastern rainforests as a new [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]].{{R|2007Yoder}}

Debt relief may help Madagascar protect its biodiversity.{{R|ScienceDaily_14Jun08}} With the [[2009 Malagasy political crisis|political crisis]] in 2009, [[Illegal logging in Madagascar|illegal logging]] has proliferated and now threatens rainforests in the northeast, including its lemur inhabitants and the ecotourism that the local communities rely upon.{{R|2009eStandardsForum}}

Captive lemur populations are maintained outside of Madagascar in many zoos, although the diversity of species is limited. Sikafas, for instance, do not survive well in captivity, so few facilities have them.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}}{{Sfn|Thalmann|Powzyk|2003|pp=1342<U+2013>1345}} The largest captive lemur population can be found at the Duke Lemur Center (DLC), whose mission includes non-invasive research, conservation (e.g. [[captive breeding]]), and public education.{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=52<U+2013>84}}  Another large lemur colony the Myakka City Lemur Reserve run by the [[Lemur Conservation Foundation]] (LCF), which also hosts lemur research.{{r|LCF_Myakka}}
{{-}}

==Cultural references==
In [[Culture of the Indian Ocean Islands#Madagascar|Malagasy culture]] lemurs, and animals in general, have [[soul]]s (''ambiroa'') which can get revenge if mocked while alive or if killed in a cruel fashion. Because of this, lemurs, like many other elements of daily life, have been a source of [[taboo]]s, known locally as ''fady'', which can be based around stories with four basic principles. A village or region may believe that a certain type of lemur may be the [[ancestor]] of the clan. They may also believe that a lemur's spirit may get revenge. Alternatively, the animal may appear as a benefactor. Lemurs are also thought to impart their qualities, good or bad, onto human babies.{{Sfn|Ruud|1970|pp=97<U+2013>101}} In general, ''fady'' extend beyond a sense of the forbidden, but can include events that bring bad luck.{{R|2001Simons}}

[[File:Indri indri 001.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=A medium-size lemur clings to a tree while looking over its shoulder. It has a very short tail and its face, hands, and upper back are black while the rest of it is white.|The [[indri]] is known locally as ''babakoto'', which translates to "Ancestor of Man".]]
One example of lemur ''fady'' told around 1970 comes from [[Ambatofinandrahana]] in the [[Fianarantsoa Province]]. According to the account, a man brought a lemur home in a trap, but alive. His children wanted to keep the lemur as a pet, but when the father told them it was not a domestic animal, the children asked to kill it. After the children tortured the lemur, it eventually died and was eaten. A short time later, all the children died of illness. As a result, the father declared that anyone who tortures lemurs for fun shall "be destroyed and have no descendants."{{Sfn|Ruud|1970|pp=97<U+2013>101}}

''Fady'' can not only help protect lemurs and their forests under stable [[socioeconomics|socioeconomic situations]], but they can also lead to discrimination and persecution if a lemur is known to bring bad fortune, for instance, if it walks through town.{{Sfn|Goodman|Ganzhorn|Rakotondravony|2003|pp=1159<U+2013>1186}}{{Sfn|Ruud|1970|pp=97<U+2013>101}} In other ways, ''fady'' does not protect all lemurs equally. For example, although the hunting and eating of certain species may be taboo, other species may not share that same protection and are therefore targeted instead.{{Sfn|Sussman|2003|pp=149<U+2013>229}}{{Sfn|Ruud|1970|pp=97<U+2013>101}} ''Fady'' can vary from village to village within the same region.{{Sfn|Sterling|2003|pp=1348<U+2013>1351}} If people move to a new village or region, their ''fady'' may not apply to the lemur species that are locally present, making them available for consumption. ''Fady'' restrictions on lemur meat can be relaxed in times of famine and drought.{{Sfn|Goodman|Ganzhorn|Rakotondravony|2003|pp=1159<U+2013>1186}}

The aye-aye is almost universally viewed unfavorably across Madagascar,{{R|2001Simons}} though the tales vary from village to village and region to region. If people see an aye-aye, they may kill it and hang the corpse on a pole near a road outside of town (so others can carry the bad fortunes away) or burn their village and move.{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|pp=205<U+2013>207}}{{Sfn|Sterling|2003|pp=1348<U+2013>1351}} The superstitions behind aye-aye ''fady'' include beliefs that they kill and eat chickens or people, that they kill people in their sleep by cutting their aortic vein,{{Sfn|Goodman|Ganzhorn|Rakotondravony|2003|pp=1159<U+2013>1186}} that they embody ancestral spirits,{{Sfn|Sterling|2003|pp=1348<U+2013>1351}} or that they warn of illness, death, or bad luck in the family.{{Sfn|Ankel-Simons|2007|pp=48<U+2013>161}}{{Sfn|Garbutt|2007|pp=205<U+2013>207}} As of 1970, the people of the [[Marolambo]] District in the [[Toamasina Province]] feared the aye-aye because they believed it had supernatural powers. Because of this, no one was allowed to mock, kill, or eat one.{{Sfn|Ruud|1970|pp=97<U+2013>101}}

There are also widespread ''fady'' about indri and sifakas. They are often protected from hunting and consumption because of their resemblance to humans and their ancestors, mostly due to their large size and upright or [[orthograde posture]]. The resemblance is even stronger for indri, which lack the long tail of most living lemurs.{{Sfn|Thalmann|Powzyk|2003|pp=1342<U+2013>1345}}{{Sfn|Irwin|2006|pp=305<U+2013>326}} Known locally as ''babakoto'' ("Ancestor of Man"), the indri is sometimes seen as the progenitor of the family or clan. There are also stories of an indri that helped a human down from a tree, so they are seen as benefactors.{{Sfn|Ruud|1970|pp=97<U+2013>101}} Other lemur ''fady'' include the belief that a wife will have ugly children if her husband kills a [[woolly lemur]], or that if a pregnant woman eats a dwarf lemur, her baby will get its beautiful, round eyes.{{Sfn|Ruud|1970|pp=97<U+2013>101}}

Lemurs have also become popular in [[Western culture]] in recent years. The original 2005 animated film ''[[Madagascar (2005 film)|Madagascar]]'' was seen by an estimated 100&nbsp;million people in theaters and 200<U+2013>300&nbsp;million people on DVD worldwide.{{LoM2 Sfn|pp=85<U+2013>88}} Prior to this movie, ''[[Zoboomafoo]]'', a [[Public Broadcasting Service]] (PBS) children's television series from 1999 to 2001,{{R|WashingtonTimes1021}} helped to popularize sifakas by featuring a live [[Coquerel's sifaka]] from the Duke Lemur Center as well as a puppet.{{R|USAToday0330}} A twenty-episode series called ''Lemur Kingdom'' (in the United States) or ''[[Lemur Street]]'' (in the United Kingdom and Canada) aired in 2008 on [[Animal Planet]]. It combined the typical animal [[documentary film|documentary]] with [[dramatic programming|dramatic narration]] to tell the story of two groups of ring-tailed lemurs at Berenty Private Reserve.{{R|NYDailyNews0208|WashingtonPost0208|AfricaNews1228|TGAM0208}}  The movie ''[[Fierce Creatures]]'' includes a lemur (as well as the main cast) on its poster.

